Besides, north Indians are not seen in much good light in south, east and west India. The extent to which north Indians and Hindi is hated can be seen clearly in a city like Bangalore, where many people from all over the country work and come in search of jobs. Many of the locals like the auto rickshaw drivers, cab drivers, shop keepers and others refuse to speak in Hindi even though many of them know the language. This is basically because they do not like the attitude of many north Indians who behave as if they own the whole country and that speaking in Hindi confers on them a special status. It is this high and mighty attitude of north Indians which is the most probable cause of the rise of outfits like the Shiv Sena and the Maharashtra Nav Nirman Sena in Maharashtra as well as outfits like the Kannada Rakshana Vedike in Karnataka.<br/><br/>
As long as people don't see a good reason for learning a language that will help them in the long run, no amount of coercion and promotion will help in popularizing the language. In fact, it will only lead to more opposition to the imposition of the language.
